<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920302-0066</DOCNO><DOCID>920302-0066.</DOCID><HL>   Roberts Seeks to Protect   Municipal Bond Buyers</HL><DATE>03/02/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7B</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)</NS><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   PHOENIX, Ariz. -- Securities and Exchange CommissionerRichard Roberts said he will push the agency to improveprotection for retail investors considering unrated municipalbonds.   Mr. Roberts said he favors a requirement that anybroker-dealer recommending unrated municipal bonds to retailcustomers would have to fully document why the bonds are asuitable investment for a particular customer. He said hewill urge the SEC's Division of Market Regulation to draftsuch a rule for the full commission to consider.</LP><TEXT>   Unrated municipal issues in such areas as nursing homes,industrial development projects and special tax districtshave accounted for about 75% of municipal bond defaults inrecent years, Mr. Robert told a Public Securities Associationconference here. Many of these defaulted bonds were sold tounsophisticated investors, he said.   Mr. Roberts, who has staked out a position as the agency'sleading member on municipal bond matters, promised greaterSEC enforcement action in the municipal market, where evenmarket participants have called for stricter regulation.   He said the SEC's enforcement efforts in the municipalarea have lagged in the past, but he told reporters theagency has been investigating several municipal securitiestransactions. He indicated he expects enforcement cases to bebrought in the future.</TEXT></DOC>